<DOC><DOCNO> AP880302-0076 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0541EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Journalists     03-02 0248</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Poland-Journalists,0255</SECOND><HEAD>Two Polish Journalists Sentenced To Prison For Spying</HEAD><DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A military court sentenced two Polishjournalists to prison after convicting them of selling informationto Western intelligence agencies, a government spokesman said.   Mariusz Dastych, 46, and Tadeusz Podwysocki, 56, both formerlyworked for the official government daily newspaper Rzeczpospolitaand were arrested last April on spying charges. Both reported onPoland's economy.   A Warsaw military court on Monday sentenced Dastych to eightyears in prison after finding him guilty of selling informationsince 1973 to the CIA on Poland's ``socio-political situation,''government spokesman Jerzy Urban said. The court also fined Dastych$790 and ordered the confiscation of all his property, said Urban,speaking at his weekly news conference Tuesday.   Podwysocki received a 1{-year prison sentence because the courtaccepted his defense that he was ``unaware that information he hadcommunicated was used for intelligence purposes,'' Urban said.   Podwysocki, one of Poland's best-known economic reporters, alsowas barred from working as a journalist for two years, fined $530and ordered to pay back all the Western currency he had receivedfor the information. Urban did not specify how much the journalistsreceived for selling the information.   Urban said Dastych and Podwysocki had cooperated with``representatives of another Western intelligence service,'' whichhe would not name.   He refused to confirm or deny reports that the second countryinvolved was Japan. According to Western press reports, they wereaccused of passing trade secrets to Japan.</TEXT></DOC>